The relational model.

Three pieces of vocabulary do almost all the work. A relation is a table. A tuple is a row. An attribute is a column.

A table has a fixed set of typed columns, and every row is one fact stated in those columns. Picture a customers table where each row holds a customer id, a name, and an email. Each row is one customer.

The key insight here is that row order is not guaranteed. The engine is free to hand back rows in any order it likes. If you want a specific order in the result, you ask for it explicitly with order by.

To make this concrete, the notebook spins up an embedded DuckDB database and creates a customers table: a customer id that is the integer primary key, a name that is not null, a unique email, and a signup date. It inserts three customers, Alice, Bob, and Carol, then selects every row back. Notice that Carol's email is null, the absence of a value, which becomes important later.
